  <p>The Rooster (<span class="chinese-char">雞</span>, jī) holds the tenth position in the Chinese zodiac cycle. In classical Chinese cosmology, the Rooster is associated with the Earthly Branch <strong>You (酉)</strong>, representing the hours of 5pm to 7pm — late afternoon when the rooster crows to gather the flock homeward, signalling the end of the working day and a time of reckoning. This placement reflects the Rooster's essential nature: vigilant, punctual, and dedicated to order.</p>
  <p>The Rooster is one of the "six domestic animals" (六畜) in Chinese tradition, valued since antiquity for both practical and symbolic reasons. The <em>Hanshu</em> (漢書, Book of Han) records that the rooster possesses "five virtues" (五德): the comb represents literary virtue (文), the spurs represent martial virtue (武), courage in battle (勇), benevolence in sharing food (仁), and reliability in crowing at dawn (信). This ancient classification established the Rooster as a model of comprehensive virtue.</p>
</section>

<section id="personality">
  <h2>Personality Traits</h2>
  <p>People born in the Year of the Rooster are characterised by <strong>observation, diligence, and courageous honesty</strong>. The Rooster's Yin Metal element provides precision and refinement — like a finely crafted blade, the Rooster's mind cuts through ambiguity to reach clarity and truth.</p>

  <h3>Core Strengths</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Observation</strong> — Roosters notice details that others miss, making them exceptional analysts and quality controllers</li>
    <li><strong>Diligence</strong> — A strong work ethic driven by the belief that consistent effort produces exceptional results</li>
    <li><strong>Punctuality</strong> — The Rooster's internal clock is remarkably precise; they value time and expect others to do the same</li>
    <li><strong>Courage</strong> — The willingness to speak uncomfortable truths and stand by unpopular positions when they are right</li>
    <li><strong>Honesty</strong> — Direct, forthright communication that others can trust absolutely, even when it stings</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Potential Challenges</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Bluntness</strong> — The commitment to honesty can become tactless criticism that wounds rather than helps</li>
    <li><strong>Perfectionism</strong> — Exacting standards applied to self and others can create an atmosphere of constant judgment</li>
    <li><strong>Vanity</strong> — The Rooster's pride in appearance and achievement can become excessive self-regard</li>
    <li><strong>Argumentativeness</strong> — The love of being right can turn conversations into debates and discussions into conflicts</li>
  </ul>
</section>

